  "prompt": "Why can't Indian government pay world bank loan by just printing money?",
  "response": "The Indian government can't simply print money to pay World Bank loans due to several important reasons:\n\n1. Inflation risks\n- Printing excessive money leads to currency devaluation\n- Increases prices of goods and services\n- Reduces purchasing power of citizens\n\n2. Economic consequences\n- Undermines national economic credibility\n- Reduces investor confidence\n- Can trigger economic instability\n\n3. International financial rules\n- World Bank loans have specific repayment terms\n- Printing money violates international lending standards\n- Would damage India's credit rating\n\n4. Monetary policy constraints\n- Central Bank (RBI) controls money supply\n- Printing money without economic productivity is discouraged\n- Can lead to hyperinflation\n\n5. Global economic reputation\n- Such actions would signal financial mismanagement\n- Could lead to reduced future lending opportunities\n- Might trigger economic sanctions\n\n6. Loan agreement terms\n- Loans require repayment in specific currencies\n- Printing local currency doesn't meet international payment standards\n\n7. Economic fundamentals\n- Loans should be repaid through genuine economic growth\n- Earnings from exports, taxes, and productivity\n\nResponsible economic management requires structured loan repayment through productive economic activities, not money printing.",
